European inflation has fallen on food
Accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in 13 countries in the euro area, with annual inflation of 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, according to the Luxembourg statistical office.
The official forecast was only 3%, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the basic interest rate, saying that the reduction would lead to inflationary spirals along with rising commodity prices and declining unemployment.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate close to 2%.
According to an analyst, the ECB is trapped in its twenty-two traps: "to talk about" inflation so that it doesn't have to act on this topic later.
In Germany, inflation of 3.3 percent in November is a twelve-year record, and in Spain it has risen from 4.1 to 3.6.
Inflation in the euro area has been pushed up by rising food and energy prices.
Future wheat notes have risen 88 percent and soy bean prices have reached the highest value since 1973.
There was also a significant increase in the cost of food oil and dairy products in 2007.
The price of oil on the world market increased by 52 percent this year, and last month it cost almost $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent this year in 2008, but will decline to 1.9 in 2009.
Analysts estimate that the level of 12-month inflation will remain at around 3% over the next 3-4 months, but the annual average rate will be 2.1%.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB will have reduced interest rates twice during 2008.
