In many places, they save on disinfectants
This year, more than 1,000 infections have been recorded in hospitals, mainly due to inadequate use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions of the hospitals, the clutter of the beds, the overburden of the staff are not conducive to stopping infections, says the head doctor of the department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
They also save on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
After a serious accident, a man found a bacteria resistant to antibiotics.
The patient was isolated.
A similar infection occurred at the beginning of the year.
He was released from the hospital in a serious car accident, but soon after he had to return with MRSA infection, and since then he has not been able to perform an important operation because of the bacteria in his body.
This year, until 10 December 1094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, head of the department of the National Centre for Epidemiology.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, the rest is unknown.
About two-thirds of the infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing the disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g., sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and are well curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inadequately, the bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop a highly resistant bacteria against antibiotics, which is rapidly spreading under inadequate hospital conditions.
In the case of transient or persistent failure of the immune system, in patients with a weakened body, elderly or low body weight, it can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning - sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections are part of the day-to-day practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the disease, MRSA is not only there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“We isolate such patients, the nursing staff provides the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients entering the hospital are initially examined for the presence of MRSA in their body, but it is not always possible to avoid infection.
I don't like sampling.
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not favorable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz says.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and elderly homes, hospitals should monitor incoming patients and should immediately isolate patients carrying MRSA.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not in fashion.
It also plays a role in the fact that the National Health Insurance Fund does not fund these studies.
Most cases are thus made public when the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, the head physician of the epidemiology centre said.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are domestic guidelines for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed in order not to develop resistance to drugs, but this is not always observed in hospitals.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
Save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA spreads most frequently from one patient to another through the mediation of health care personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves, the use of masks plays a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in this in hospitals.
MRSA is spread by drip infection and contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the hospital rooms are often crowded, often very close to each other beds, although from an epidemiological point of view patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, it can also be seen, noted Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, that in hospitals in unfavourable financial situations, they save on disinfectants, few nurses, many patients, so there is even more chance of infection.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, where appropriate precautions are taken, there is less evidence of such an infection or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Managing the MRSA infection is a huge expense for health insurers, and they are fighting it everywhere.
In England, for example, he included in the government program the prevention and reduction of MRSA.
It appears that the program is successful, according to the data reported, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) include the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
