Political Capital: the Hungarian Guard raises the risk of the country
The activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded with the support of the Jobbik Hungary Movement in August of this year, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital.
The company’s “risk warning” stated that the biggest political risk associated with the activities of the Hungarian Guard was that “in the short term, even violent ethnic clashes may arise as the ethnic tension between the gypsy and non-gypsy populations in Hungary escalates”.
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to be aimed at provoking such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this is due to one of the main omissions of Hungarian political actors: "The public debate on the Roma issue has been handed over to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the gypsy-Hungarian opposite."
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts occurring, they say.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard have “significantly worsened the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of faith in the stability and democratic development of the country”.
It is recalled that since the autumn of 2006 it has gained increasing publicity and momentum as part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary, and that since the summer of 2007 several organisations called themselves "national self-defence" associations have been established in Hungary.
“The common feature of these compacts is that they define themselves as a non-governmental organisation, while they openly proclaim the preparation of their members, whether armed or not, for defence (catastrophic, defense, law enforcement) tasks, and also for the incompetence of the police, the army, or the state,” they added.
They noted that all this is done in accordance with a method which, on the basis of the political and anti-party opposition of society, seeks to put various political aspirations in civil robes.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association are therefore not only intended to avoid legal failures of judicial registration in the case of these associations, but also a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk factor for neighbourhood relations.
“In recent months, Hungarian Guards have been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring states, and some ultranationalist political actors in neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the formation of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region,” he added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, so the political risks for the region as a whole have increased.
As it was written, the operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to the activities of the Bulgarian National Guard, the establishment of which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
Against the background of the formation of the Bulgarian Guard are the mass Roma riots that erupted in one of Sofia's districts (Krasna Poljana).
BNU took advantage of this decision to establish a guard, saying that the organization’s goal was “national self-defense.”
