In Hungary, the law accurately marks the red-letter days, and around the holidays the workday reorganization has become a common practice, from which next year it will be less.
The holiday is not uniform in the EU and America.
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between national and state holidays and holidays.
Holidays are mostly associated with church holidays and important historical events.
We also celebrate the New Year with us: the last day of the Old Year and the first day of the new year are both holidays - the latter just so that the New Year's Evers can relax.
We have a total of 11 red-letter holidays all year round.
National holiday is also the 15th of March and 23th of October, commemorating the Revolution of 1848, and the Memorial Day of the 1956 Revolution.
On August 20th, we celebrate the foundation of the state, on May 1st, and on November 1st and 2nd, we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, we have a two-day celebration of Easter, Pentecost and Christmas.
As state, national, or even religious holidays rarely fall on the weekend according to the calendar, it became a practice to shift the working day in cases where we would only work for one day before or after the red-letter holiday.
True, the price of extended weekends is that on the preceding Saturdays we will not stay away from work-school.
The exact time of the day immediately before or after the holiday has to be worked out has been regulated by a separate regulation by the Minister of Labour for many years.
The legislation covers all employers and their employees, both public employees and those in a public service relationship.
However, it does not affect service companies and institutions operating without interruption and, as a result of its intended purpose, also operating on holidays.
This year’s work schedule changes only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24th, life in the country almost stops, since experience shows that the days between Christmas and New Year’s Eve are “slowed” by the majority of people, or used for this purpose to save their freedom.
Next year, we will have more holidays in the middle of the week and at the end of the week, so there will be less workday shifts than this year.
First, the calendar changes around the holiday of work so that employees can stay at home for four days.
Saturday 26 April will be a working day for Friday 2 May.
The second transfer is related to the 23rd October holiday: you will have to work on Saturday, October 18th instead of Friday 24th.
However, the end of the year can be entirely in the spirit of the holiday next year, since from December 24 almost everywhere a nonstop break is held even if the New Year’s Eve falls on Wednesday.
