Spectacular repair at the space station
Astronaut Scott Parazynski and the crew of the International Space Station (ISS) had to work more than seven hours in space to perform a spectacular repair of the solar panel, which is essential for the scientific activity of the station.
This dangerous spacewalk proved to be a record in many ways: the repair took a very long time, there was very little time to design it, and it had to be carried out away from the housing modules, with the tools "barked" by the astronauts.
The problem arose on Tuesday when astronauts separated the Harmony module from Discovery. It is a huge cylindrical element that will soon be the site of European and Japanese scientific laboratory activities (see box).
This module is a kind of gateway to laboratory modules.
However, you need to take care of your power supply.
The second task of the crew was, therefore, to move one of the modules that produced electricity with the help of the 17.5-ton solar panels, which was already on the ISS, to its final location.
The crew then began opening the 76-meter-wide solar panels of the module.
One of the harmonically foldable boards was then damaged by a cable trapped about 1 meter in length.
To avoid further injury, the opening of the board was not continued.
The mission of the astronauts was originally to take a control walk from the Discovery shuttle and then repair another solar panel with a faulty rotation system. Instead, they had to devote their full time to repairing the damaged solar panel.
Scott Parazynski was chosen to perform the stunt by hanging on a 30-metre robot arm attached to the crane at the station.
He's one of NASA's best "space walkers."
It has a tall, strong, extremely skilful, muscular upper body and a long arm.
A 46-year-old man with a doctor’s degree had to “operation” the “damaged” solar panel.
After carefully assessing the damage, he cut off the faulty cable and fixed the damaged area with a few "rails".
In his work, he was assisted by another "spacewalker" who remained near the safe passage, as well as other astronauts inside, including the captain of the crew, Peggy Whitson.
The tool he used, a mini hockey stick fitted with insulation against the hundreds of volts of solar panels, was hatched and "barkled" by the station's astronauts.
After the operation, Scott Parazynski waited for his associates to open the board completely, and only then packed his tools and returned to the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts took a half-day rest, and today, seven of them returned to the Discovery shuttle to begin their return home on Wednesday.
