Compressed memories
After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive became public, documenting the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archive documents, which occupy 27 kilometers of shelves in Bad Arolsen, Hessen Province, have so far only been researched for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. they have provided unique and name-specific insights for the victims or their descendants of the past.
Eleven states that manage the archives, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed in May 2006 to open the archives for researchers and historians.
After all states ratified the convention, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential Information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen Archives allows historians to conduct research “on the relocation of prisoners, on the inhabitants of camps and on the health of forced labourers,” explains Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the public disclosure of documents because they contain names and thus confidential information.
This may include the presumed homosexuality or mental disability of some of the deported victims.
The lists of concentration camps and the arrest warrants issued by Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons. The aim was to search for civilians deported or sentenced to forced labour on the basis of these lists and to provide evidence of their internment, on the basis of which they could receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees are currently working on processing tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, a part of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of paramount importance.
"These documents basically contain nothing new," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Centre for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
