There have been many rumours about the new music festival in Philadelphia organized by C3 Presents. However, now the company that organized and promoted the event announced that the Vineland music festival will be held in New Jersey in cooperation with British producer Melvin Benn and the Festival Republic.
“It’s an honor for us to work with someone who is the launcher of today’s American festival movement,” Charlie Jones of C3 told Billboard.com.
The C3 also organizes the Lollapalooza Festival in Chicago and the Austin City Limits Music Festival.
The Vineland Festival in New Jersey is held in the summer, so it will be possible to camp.
The festival takes place between August 8 and 10, in a private area of 500 acres, about 40 minutes from Philadelphia.
Melvin Benn, formerly known as Mean Fiddler, is one of the most respected festival organizers in the world.
In 1989, he began organizing the British Reading Festival, which attracts around 80,000 visitors each year.
In 1999, Melvin Benn continued to expand his range by organizing the Leeds Festival, and in 2006 the Festival Republic brought the Latitude Festival to life in Henham Park, Suffolk.
Since 2002, Melvin Benn has been co-owner of the Glastonbury Festival’s production, licensing and organization tasks. This festival can now accommodate up to 177,500 people.
C3 co-worker Charlie Jones called Glastonbury Festival the "most inspiring event" he ever attended, adding that his company and Melvin Benn's company are working in parallel to enrich the region with a European-style festival event.
“We’ve chosen the Philadelphia location before, and together with the Fairmount Parks Committee, we’ve worked hard to host this festival in the center of Philadelphia,” said Charlie Jones.
“We have been engaged with the city and the Commission has shown great enthusiasm for our plan.
Unfortunately, however, due to the political maneuvers of the city administration, the organization has failed,” said Charlie Jones.
“We were fortunate to talk about this with Melvin Benn, and now we are preparing to host a huge festival at another unique venue that ultimately serves the interests of the people of Philadelphia.”
The C3 Presents revived the Lollapalooza festival in 2005 in Grant Park, Chicago, after proving its exceptional talent for festival organizers with the Austin City Limits music festival in 2002.
The gross revenue of the two events in 2007 was 9.8 million dollars and 11.3 million dollars.
Both festivals were held in urban locations.
“The European concept of Melvin Benn is based on the rural festival, while our festivals usually take place in urban green areas,” says Charlie Jones.
Our goal is to combine the two models in some way, thereby creating both the rural atmosphere in Europe and the familiar urban feeling in America.”
Vineland is located about halfway between Philadelphia and Atlantic City.
“Vineland’s population, and even the mayor himself, are enthusiastically supporting the event,” says Charlie Jones.
Although he does not talk about the details of the agreement, he says that “the conditions are favorable enough to allow investment in such an event at a location that hopefully will host the festival for a long time.”
According to Charlie Jones, the festival will be of a “heavy” size, with a capacity roughly equal to the capacity of 80,000 people at the Bonnaroo music festival in Tennessee.
The group has already received an invitation to the event, but nothing is final at the time of the press release.
“Vineland will basically be a rock festival, but we’re planning a variety of music offerings so that everyone can find what they want in it,” says Charlie Jones.
Jones and his two partners, Charlie Walker and Charles Attal, make up the C3 company, which received the "best independent event organizer" award at the most recent Billboard Touring Awards.
