Congress approves receipt of MiFID that came into force on November 1
In parallel to the parliamentary process, which was concluded today by a congressional vote approving the Senate amendments, the government has initiated a social dialogue on the legislation on which the law is based, so that both can take effect before the end of the year.
The representatives of the various groups unanimously highlighted the efforts of the representatives and senators in negotiations and agreements to develop the most favourable normative protection for investors and to regulate the activities of the companies in detail in order to operate effectively in the market.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, allows for the modernisation of financial markets, while at the same time strengthening investor protection, broadening the supervisory rights of the Spanish National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and promoting cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new directive will enable financial advisory services to be provided to specialised companies, but also to natural or legal persons, and, in addition to securities distribution companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies, will create a new form of financial services company (ESIS), namely financial advisory companies (AFIs).
In addition, the law increases the number of systems capable of carrying out operations involving funds, thus adding multilateral trading platforms and internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets, which compete with current stock exchange players.
In addition, the Act obliges investment service providers to market information on the key aspects of their business profile, their risk-taking and risk management methods, and to facilitate the control of CNMV, to keep records of all operations carried out.
The Economic Committee of Congress has introduced a number of amendments. Of these, it is of paramount importance that securitised debts are treated as "complex" funds due to the high risk they pose to the investor. This has been confirmed by the U.S. High Risk Mortgage Credit (subprime).
On the other hand, the transposition of the directive has also been used to legally outline the scope of activities of those with economic and entrepreneurial qualifications, 30 years after the Royal Decree defining the professional functions that can be performed exclusively by economists came into force in 1977.
The Senate has proposed the creation of new players in the financial sector, such as an intermediary agent who works for someone else’s account, does not need the permission of CNMV, and can sell products or acquire customers to multiple investment companies at the same time.
