What insurance is right for me?
Car insurance, which means safety for the owner of a car, is a significant expense to the various damages and depends on several factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining a driving licence, family status, type and nature of use of the car to be insured.
Buying a car is just the first step.
In fact, choosing the right insurance is often more difficult than deciding which car you want.
First of all, we need to be aware of what this is about.
Car insurance is an agreement between the insurance company and the insured.
This agreement takes the form of an insurance contract, which states that the insurance company undertakes to compensate for the fixed insurance premium in the event of a damage event.
The insurance premium is basically the amount paid for insurance, which is determined by taking into account various factors, such as age, gender, date of obtaining a driving licence, family status, the type of car to be insured, its use, and so on.
Insurance companies determine the insurance premium on the basis of statistics, i.e. a higher amount is paid by the person who represents a higher accident risk.
That’s why women over the age of 25 or women pay less because, according to statistics, they pose a lower risk because they are more cautious.
Similarly, according to the findings, insurance companies have concluded that married people also cause fewer accidents than lonely people.
The frequency of use of the car is crucial.
With more frequent use, the possibility of an accident increases.
When determining the insurance premium, insurance companies take into account a number of factors.
Therefore, the owner needs to look closely to choose the most suitable form of insurance for his profile.
In the following, we present the most important factors in the selection process, in order to best adapt to the needs of the insured and to establish an acceptable price.
When concluding an insurance contract, people under the age of 25 must account for a number of disadvantages, such as a lack of driving experience and the freshness of the driving licence.
While it is best to be protected against all hazards, there are more economical solutions.
More cautious drivers can make full insurance by self-insurance, which will ensure against all hazards, and the price will also be affordable.
In this type of contract, the insured pays part of the damage.
“The amount of the self-financing paid by the insured depends on the insurance premium; the higher the premium, the lower the self-financing,” says Luis Noguera, head of First Europa in Spain.
Another option is extended liability insurance for third parties, when the client provides himself/herself against damage caused to others, but not against damage caused in his/her own car.
In addition, you will be insured against theft, fire damage and loss of the car.
A good advice.
If you are not 25 years old, be careful and avoid accidents as this will affect the bonus and reduce the amount you will pay in the future.
The bonuses are called bonuses compared to the basic rates of the insurance company.
The penalty imposed against the base rate is called molasses.
"The amount of bonus and Raspberry depends on the insurance company and its profits.
If the company has had a good year, you can afford to raise the bonus amount,” Noguera explains.
Once the age of 25 has been exceeded, it is easier for owners to make adequate insurance, as the risk of accidents is reduced thanks to the experience gained over the years.
Then we advise you to make a full insurance with your own share.
"In general, young people are not yet able to properly apply their experience in each accident, and even when driving," says the director of the European insurance company in Spain, adding that the majority of accidents occur in the second year of driving, when drivers have already overcome the fear of beginners.
If the insured person is already married but does not yet have children, it is best to make a full insurance, of course, if his financial options allow it.
Insurance companies consider married couples with children to be the least risky customers, so in their case the fee payable is also lower.
In this case, it is best to have a complete insurance with a self-exclusion (this can reach 300 euros) or, if they have a higher bonus, they can extend the insurance from the third year of the vehicle to the damage caused to others.
“They drive more calmly, but at the same time they have greater purchasing power and can afford to have a higher share of the self,” says Luis Noguera.
In the case of pensioners, full insurance is recommended with a self-exclusion (around 150 euros) or, in the case of a higher bonus, liability insurance can be extended.
Car insurance is very important, not only because it means protection for the owner in the event of damage, but also because it means a large expense, so it is essential to choose the right form of insurance.
