New fears about the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas exchange between Ukraine and Russia has been renewed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be transported to Western Europe.
The vast majority of Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is transited through Ukraine and disputes between the two nations are always under great notice.
Kiev has said that if Moscow increases the gas price paid by Ukrainians, they will also pay Russia a higher transit cost.
A previous debate between the two countries last year resulted in a reduction in supplies to EU countries.
The most recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow is related to the attempt by the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned natural gas monopoly Gazprom to reach an agreement on the gas price to be paid by Ukraine to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it would have to make a 50 % increase compared to the price agreement with Ukraine for gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan for 2008.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of a shipment from Gazprom to Ukraine.
“It is important to argue in line with one of the most important natural gas transit states during the negotiations,” Ukrainian Minister of Economic Affairs Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
"Changes in gas prices should be linked to our debate on the cost of transits (and transits to Western Europe) across Ukraine."
As a result of the recent significant gas flood between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom closed the gas tap to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like drop in exports to Western Europe, which also pushed prices to a large extent.
A quarter of the European Union’s gas supply is Russian gas.
Russia has the world’s largest natural gas reserves, but most of them are still unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom will complement its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The NHS "must check for foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS committees should improve the control of criminal records of workers from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal was presented by Chief Auditor Robert Black after a foreign-citizen doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate data on the number of overseas workers.
At the same time, it also pointed out, through a sample of five health authorities, key controls that were properly carried out.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the main auditor checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
28-year-old Bilal Abdullah, a doctor of Iraqi origin at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep drove to the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of the three doctors questioned by the Old Bailey court in October on charges of attempted car bomb attacks in the UK.
In the case of their employees from overseas countries, the NHS committees shall verify the existence of the qualifications and work experience of the workers concerned and their availability with the necessary permits to work in the United Kingdom prior to the start of employment.
Although the Scottish Health Committees use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not entitled to obtain such information from outside the UK.
The main auditor's report proposed, among other things, that the committees introduce a Code of Conduct for the Criminal Records Office, which facilitates the employer's control processes with different overseas countries.
“Although we found evidence of such checks in the records of staff, they are not regularly carried out,” the report said.
According to Black, the Scottish NHS performs its own pre-employment screening procedure at a high level, adding: “Our report highlights the areas of the system that can be developed in order to provide up-to-date information on the number of personnel of the NHS overseas.”
According to Dr. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, “it is highly improbable” that pre-employment controls would allow us to identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
"According to the report, the current pre-employment controls are working well in NHS Scotland and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent," he added.
According to the Scottish health authorities, the current number of their overseas employees, consisting of doctors and nurses, is 1,161.
However, the main auditor pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, which is partly explained by the fact that it is a problem for committees to identify employees on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures in the Ayrshire and Arran regions, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and the NHS authorities in Lothian are highly coordinated.
These procedures covered the verification of passports, work permits and documents certifying professional qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently examining the guidelines and guidelines for the pre-employment controls of employees of the NHS from overseas countries.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I am delighted that this task has been carried out following the attack on Glasgow Airport.
He added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, will take into account the proposals contained in the report and will ensure that the up-to-date guide on pre-employment controls for the entire staff corps, including those from overseas, reflects the best practical application. The updated version is planned to be published next month.
