Venus is Earth's Devil's Twin Brother
Despite the harsh atmosphere of Venus, it resembles Earth more than previously assumed: in its atmosphere, the European "Venus Express" spacecraft discovered lightnings and wind vortexes on its heels, such as those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have speculated that Venus is lightning.
The European "Venus Express" spacecraft has provided evidence - it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at a height of about 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russell, a fellow at the University of California in Los Angeles, a science magazine called Nature.
According to the famous "high soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightnings: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: “If there was ever life there, it could have been in very early times,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington.
Currently, there is hardly any living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperature values sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's hellish twin, but it's still his twin," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus is so similar in mass and size to Earth on a completely different evolutionary path.
The launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, because since the early 1990s, no probe has been on its way specifically to find this planet.
According to researchers, the latest research published in several "Nature" articles proves not only the uniqueness of Venus in the solar system.
“They’re also saying that the similarity of the neighboring planet to the Earth is greater than we first assumed,” Esa said.
In addition to the already known Arctic whirlwind, the researchers also discovered an even faster moving cloud vortex on the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents in the Earth’s winter hemisphere, according to a team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Institute of Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The mass of the second innermost planet of the Solar System is almost the same as that of the Earth, and its diameter of 12,100 kilometres is almost the same as that of the Earth.
The celestial body, also known as the Evening Star, orbits the Sun in less than 225 days.
However, it turns much slower around its own axis: a Venus day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus’ surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius, coupled with 92 bar pressure, is barely reminiscent of Earth, scientists are beginning to believe that both planets were created in completely similar conditions.
Both of them had water, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while Venus departed into the universe.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is bound up in carbon deposits, it forms a large part of the atmosphere on Venus.
