The prehistory is a confusing chain of long and complicated, artistic and curatorial stunts.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxes" in New York in 1964 - painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of "Brillo" soap powder.
At his 1968 exhibition in Moderna Museet - with Warhol's consent - hundreds of Brillo crates made of cardboard were exhibited: these (for cost-saving reasons) were not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo board factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their templates and simple exhibition pieces.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to manufacture some of the Brillo villages in Sweden, which were not produced in Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the age now speak of roughly fifteen crates that, at the time, were certified as Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box under the designation "Stockholm-type" rightfully entered the history of art and auction.
Some were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968, about a hundred wooden crates were produced and produced in Sweden, which Warhol left for him.
